On average, the bat gut microbial communities were dominated by Proteobacteria (70.9%) and Firmicutes (24.9%), whereas the bat guano was dominated by Actinobacteria (32.5%), Proteobacteria (38.4%), and AD3 (18.9%), as indicated in (Fig. 5
). A higher alpha diversity (Choa1 index) was also found in the guano sample than the gut microbiomes of the Arwah cave samples (Fig. 6
). The results indicate that Proteobacteria is the most dominant bacterial phylum in both types of bat samples. Bacterial phyla such as Actinobacteria, Acidobacteria, and AD3 were abundant in the guano samples but were not found or had very low numbers in the gut samples.
